s, see complex connections, excellent spatial vision, very good leadership qualities, unfriendly, eats unhealthily. B: very conscientious, handles stress well, good at assessing weather conditions, excellent computer skills, pretentious, sometimes adopts wrong tone. C: can make correct decisions quickly, difficulty communicating ideas, egocentric, not very willing to further his education, puts concern for others above everything, excellent attention skills. D: responds to unexpected events adequately, can concentrate very well, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously, moody, loner.\n\nWe also have info from Agent 2 (our own earlier message) about A being show-off, not open to new ideas, B weak memory for numbers, nasty remarks, C keeps calm in crisis, understands complicated technology, D know-it-all, hot temper. But those are not from our own dataset but from other agents. We can incorporate them as \"information from others\". So we have a fairly complete picture.\n\nNow we need to decide current preferred candidate. Previously we favored A. But after seeing that D lacks teamwork/communication, that doesn't affect A. We need to weigh all candidates again.\n\nLet's list strengths/weaknesses:\n\nA: Anticipates dangerous situations, sees complex connections, excellent spatial vision, very good leadership. Weaknesses: unfriendly, eats unhealthily, show-off, not open to new ideas. Leadership good but interpersonal issues.\n\nB: Very conscientious, handles stress well, good at assessing weather, excellent computer skills. Weaknesses: pretentious, wrong tone, weak memory for numbers, nasty remarks.\n\nC: Can make correct decisions quickly, puts concern for others above everything, excellent attention, keeps calm in crisis, understands complicated technology. Weaknesses: difficulty communicating ideas, egocentric, not willing to further education.\n\nD: Responds adequately to unexpected events, concentrates, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously. Weaknesses: moody, loner, know-it-all, hot temper, no positive teamwork/communication.\n\nNow evaluate criteria:\n\nReliability/responsibility: D takes responsibility seriously, but moody/loner may affect reliability. B conscientious. C puts concern for others, 100% reliable? Not explicitly but seems reliable. A leadership but unfriendly.\n\nTechnical/cognitive: A spatial vision, complex connections, anticipation. B weather assessment, computer. C quick decisions, attention, tech understanding. D problem solving, concentration.\n\nCalmness/pressure: B handles stress well. C keeps calm in crisis. D responds adequately. A not mentioned. So B and C strong.\n\nDecision-making: A anticipates, C quick decisions, D solves problems, B weather assessment.\n\nTeamwork/communication: C puts concern for others, positive crew atmosphere (from other agents). A leadership but unfriendly, show-off. B pretentious, nasty remarks. D no positive info, moody, loner.\n\nProfessional development: B computer skills, maybe growth. A not open to new ideas. C not willing to further education. D weak leadership.\n\nOverall, C seems strongest on teamwork, calmness, decision-making, technical, reliability. Weaknesses: communication difficulty, egocentric, not willing to further education. But his concern for others and positive crew atmosphere may offset communication issues.\n\nB is strong on stress handling and technical, but interpersonal issues (pretentious, nasty remarks) could be severe for crew.\n\nA has strong technical anticipation and leadership but interpersonal issues (unfriendly, show-off, not open to new ideas) could affect crew.\n\nD lacks teamwork, has temperament issues.\n\nThus I would now favor Candidate C. This aligns with Agent 3's preference. So I will update my vote to Candidate C.\n\nWe should mention that new info confirms D lacks teamwork, reinforcing that D is not suitable. We should note uncertainties: C's communication difficulty could be mitigated; egocentric attitude may affect crew; lack of willingness to further education may affect long-term. What would change vote: evidence of strong teamwork/communication for A or B, or evidence that C's communication issues cause safety concerns.\n\nNow produce public message with these points, referencing evidence from our own info and from other agents (Agent 3's preference, Agent 1's answer). Also ask any further question? Possibly ask Agent 1 if they have any positive info about A's calmness under pressure. But not required.\n\nProceed."}
